1
00:00:00,320 --> 00:00:05,090
If Channel N cuts in, say, Stop, then switch channels.

2
00:00:05,199 --> 00:00:11,410
To make the switch, all you must do is think of one positive quality about the individual.

3
00:00:11,680 --> 00:00:18,850
In true chain reaction style, this one thought will lead to another and another, and you will be glad.

4
00:00:19,439 --> 00:00:29,410
When you are alone, you and only you can decide whether you will listen to Channel P or Channel N. But when you are talking with someone else,

5
00:00:29,520 --> 00:00:33,090
that person has a measure of control over how you think.

6
00:00:33,600 --> 00:00:39,969
We must remember that most people do not understand the concepts of thinking right toward people.

7
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:44,209
So it's a very common experience for people to come rushing to you,

8
00:00:44,320 --> 00:00:48,530
just aching to say something negative about a person you both know.

9
00:00:48,719 --> 00:00:53,890
A co-worker wants to tell you about the objectionable qualities of another employee.

10
00:00:54,080 --> 00:00:58,290
A neighbor wants to let you know the domestic problems of another neighbor.

11
00:00:58,480 --> 00:01:04,370
or a customer wants to itemize the faults of his competitor, whom you will call on next.

12
00:01:05,040 --> 00:01:07,170
Thoughts breed like thoughts.

13
00:01:07,280 --> 00:01:11,890
There is real danger that if you listen to negative comments about another person,

14
00:01:12,080 --> 00:01:14,930
you too will go negative toward that person.

15
00:01:15,199 --> 00:01:21,410
In fact, if you are not on guard, you may actually find yourself adding fuel to the fire with,

16
00:01:21,680 --> 00:01:24,610
yes, and that's not all, did you hear?

17
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:26,130
type of comment.

18
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:28,689
These things backfire.

19
00:01:28,800 --> 00:01:30,050
Boomerang.

20
00:01:30,320 --> 00:01:41,810
There are two ways to prevent others from switching us from Channel P to Channel N. One way is to switch topics as quickly and quietly as possible with some remark like,

21
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:46,209
Pardon me, John, but while I think of it, I've been meaning to ask you.

22
00:01:46,480 --> 00:01:51,410
A second way is to excuse yourself with a Sorry, John, I'm late now,

23
00:01:51,520 --> 00:01:53,570
or I have a deadline to meet.

24
00:01:53,600 --> 00:01:55,009
Will you excuse me?

25
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,370
Make a forceful promise to yourself.

26
00:01:58,640 --> 00:02:01,489
Refuse to let others prejudice your thinking.

27
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:09,969
Stay tuned to Channel P. Once you've mastered the technique of thinking only good thoughts about people,

28
00:02:10,160 --> 00:02:12,370
greater success is guaranteed.

29
00:02:12,719 --> 00:02:21,170
Let me tell you what an unusually successful insurance salesman told me about how thinking good thoughts about people pays off for him.

30
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:27,570
When I first got in the insurance business, he began, the going was tough, believe me.

31
00:02:27,760 --> 00:02:33,090
At first, it seemed there were about as many competing agents as there were prospects.

32
00:02:33,280 --> 00:02:42,050
And I soon learned what all insurance men know, that nine prospects out of ten firmly believe they don't need any more insurance.

33
00:02:42,480 --> 00:02:49,170
I'm doing well, but let me tell you, it's not because I know a lot about the technical side of insurance.

34
00:02:49,439 --> 00:02:58,850
That's important, don't misunderstand me, but there are men trying to sell insurance who know policies and contracts better than I. In fact,

35
00:02:58,959 --> 00:03:06,930
I know one man who wrote a book about insurance, but he couldn't sell a policy to a man who knew he had only five days to live.

36
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:11,170
My success, he continued, is based on one thing.

37
00:03:11,439 --> 00:03:14,530
I like, really like the guy I'm selling.

38
00:03:14,640 --> 00:03:17,489
Let me say again, I really like him.

39
00:03:17,840 --> 00:03:23,330
Some of my fellow salesmen try to pretend they like the other fellow, but this won't work.

